  {panel}

Lets say we have the changes:

{noformat}
11:30 -> 12:00       -> 1:00
Open     Progress       QA
{noformat}

This will produce the Index entries:

{noformat}
[11:30, 12:00) -> Open
[12:00, 1:00)  -> Progress
[1:00, +Inf) -> QA
{noformat}

Now lets say we run the query {{status was progress on -1h}} at 1:30. This basically means {{status was progress [12:00, 1:00)}}. We generate the Lucene query {{endChange > 12:00 and startChange < 1:00 and newValue = "progress"}}. This is good and correct.

Now lets say you had this:

{noformat}
11:30 -> 12:00   ->  12:00    -> 1:00
Open     Starting    Progress    QA
{noformat}

This will produce the Index entries:

{noformat}
[11:30, 12:00) -> Open
[12:00, 12:00) -> Starting
[12:00, 1:00)  -> Progress
[1:00, +Inf) -> QA
{noformat}

Now lets say we run the query {{status was starting on -1h}} at 1:30. We generate the Lucene query {{endChange > 12:00 and startChange < 1:00 and newValue = "starting"}}. Unfortunately this will not match the zero length "Starting" change at 12:00. This is no way to match this change using ON. *THIS IS THE BUG*

Further assume that the history is actually following.

{noformat}
11:30 -> 12:01   ->  12:01    -> 1:00
Open     Starting    Progress    QA
{noformat}

This will produce the Index entries:

{noformat}
[11:30, 12:01) -> Open
[12:01, 12:01) -> Starting
[12:01, 1:00)  -> Progress
[1:00, +Inf) -> QA
{noformat}

In this case we will match the zero length "Starting" change item with the query {{endChange > 12:00 and startChange < 1:00 and newValue = "starting"}}.

Before you say this will never happen, many of our databases (e.g MySQL and Oracle) only store dates down to second precision. Things like SOAP clients, workflow functions, Jelly scripts etc could quite easily create a zero length change.

